===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|sceap|scēap|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|skēpan|lang=gem-pro}} (compare {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|skiep|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|frr|-}} {{term|schäip|lang=frr}} (also Fering-Öömrang dialect ''sjep''; Sölring dialect ''sjip''; Heligoland dialect ''skeap''), {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|schaap|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Schaf|lang=de}}), beside {{recons|keppôn|lang=gem-pro}} (compare {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|kjappi||he-goat|lang=non}}, {{etyl|de|-}} dialect {{term|Kippe||newborn calf|lang=de}}), from Sarmato-Scythian (compare {{etyl|os|-}} {{term|цæу|tr=cæw|lang=os||goat}}, {{etyl|fa|-}} {{term|چپش||yearling goat|tr=čapiš|lang=fa}}).<ref>Vladimir Orel, ''A Handbook of Germanic Etymology'', s.vv. "*keppōn", "*skēpan" (Leiden: Brill, 2003), 213, 340.</ref> The same Iranian word was borrowed into {{etyl|sq|-}} {{term|cjap|lang=sq}}, {{term|sqap|lang=sq||he-goat}} and Slavic (cf. {{etyl|pl|-}} {{term|cap|lang=pl}}).

